.elsevier.com/content/author/author_id/57670244900</author-url><affiliation id="60104842" href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60104842"/></author></dc:creator><dc:description><abstract xmlns="" original="y" xml:lang="eng"><publishercopyright>Â© 2025 The Authors. Published by American Chemical Society.</publishercopyright><ce:para>In situ spectroscopic data collection methods, such as those from infrared or Raman spectroscopy, can provide real-time and continuous information for process monitoring. However, to obtain useful information such as reaction kinetics, the collected data must be decoupled into component concentrations and pure component spectra, a challenging problem due to overlapping signals from species in the mixture. As a result, accurate and flexible methods to address these issues remain a highly active research area. In this work, we investigate a silanol polymer end-capping reaction. Three experiments were conducted at three different reaction temperatures, and spectroscopic data were collected using in situ near-infrared spectroscopy (NIR). The pure component absorbance for silanol experiences hydrogen-bonding interactions as well as temperature dependence, providing less information that can be shared across experiments. To address this, we propose several candidate models with varying levels of complexity, including a simple model for hydrogen bonding. We formulate and solve the mechanistic model using a nonlinear programming-based simultaneous solution strategy to obtain estimates of global and local parameters. Because of the nonlinear programming formulation, which utilizes exact second derivatives, this approach leads to the direct calculation of 95% confidence regions for all estimates. Using statistical criteria to select a preferred model from among those developed for this reaction, we apply the Bayesian notion of probability shares to select the most likely model from the experimental data.</ce:para></abstr